    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Naming Sex Offenders On the Internet Gains</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <dateline>TRENTON</dateline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New Jersey legislative committees move closer to amending state Constitution to permit posting of names, addresses and descriptions of convicted sex offenders on Internet (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Legislative committees yesterday moved closer to amending the State Constitution to permit officials to post convicted sex offenders' names, addresses and physical descriptions on the Internet.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Legislative committees yesterday moved closer to amending the State Constitution to permit officials to post convicted sex offenders' names, addresses and physical descriptions on the Internet.</p>
        <p>The proposed constitutional amendment, which was approved by the Senate Judiciary and Assembly Law and Public Safety committees, is designed to allay concerns about challenges to a local notification procedure known as Megan's Law in state courts. Megan's Law, which requires the state to warn neighbors when a sex offender moves to a community, has been on hold since April, when a federal appeals court said it would review its fairness.</p>
        <p>METRO NEWS BRIEFS: NEW JERSEY</p>
      </block>
